specialcase.p:
        The standard coordinate vectors in \R^n always form an orthonormal set.  For instance, in \R^3 we check that

          \vec{1 0 0}\cdot\vec{0 1 0} = 0 \qquad
          \vec{1 0 0}\cdot\vec{0 0 1} = 0 \qquad
          \vec{0 1 0}\cdot\vec{0 0 1} = 0.

        Since e_i\cdot e_i = 1 for all i=1,2,3, this shows that \{e_1,e_2,e_3\} is orthonormal.

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5, myxyz, thin border nodes]
  \draw[grid lines, transformxy] (-1.5,-1.5) grid (1.5,1.5);
  \draw[->] (-1.5,0,0) -- (1.5,0,0);
  \draw[->] (0,-1.5,0) -- (0,1.5,0);
  \draw[->] (0,0,-1.5) -- (0,0,1.5);
  \coordinate (e1) at (1,0,0);
  \coordinate (e2) at (0,1,0);
  \coordinate (e3) at (0,0,1);
  \coordinate (o) at (0,0,0);
  \pic[draw, right angle len=3mm] {right angle=(e1)--(o)--(e2)};
  \pic[draw, right angle len=3mm] {right angle=(e1)--(o)--(e3)};
  \pic[draw, right angle len=3mm] {right angle=(e2)--(o)--(e3)};
  \draw[vector, seq1] (0,0,0) to["$e_1$" pos=.8] (1,0,0);
  \draw[vector, seq2] (0,0,0) to["$e_2$" below=1pt] (0,1,0);
  \draw[vector, seq3] (0,0,0) to["$e_3$"] (0,0,1);
  \point at (0,0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}

solution.p:
          We check that

            \vec{1 1 1}\cdot\vec{1 -2 1} = 0
            \qquad \vec{1 1 1}\cdot\vec{1 0 -1} = 0
            \qquad \vec{1 -2 1}\cdot\vec{1 0 -1} = 0.

          Therefore, \cB is orthogonal.

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5, myxyz, x={(-1.2cm,-.5cm)}, y={(1cm,-.2cm)}, thin border nodes]
  \draw[grid lines, transformxy] (-2,-2) grid (2,2);
  \draw[->] (-2.5,0,0) -- (2.5,0,0);
  \draw[->] (0,-2.5,0) -- (0,2.5,0);
  \draw[->] (0,0,-1.5) -- (0,0,1.5);
  \coordinate (v1) at (1,1,1);
  \coordinate (v2) at (-1,2,-1);
  \coordinate (v3) at (1,0,-1);
  \coordinate (o) at (0,0,0);
  \pic[draw, right angle len=3mm] {right angle=(v1)--(o)--(v2)};
  \pic[draw, right angle len=3mm] {right angle=(v1)--(o)--(v3)};
  \pic[draw, right angle len=3mm] {right angle=(v2)--(o)--(v3)};
  \draw[vector, seq1] (0,0,0) to (v1);
  \draw[vector, seq2] (0,0,0) to (v2);
  \draw[vector, seq3] (0,0,0) to (v3);
  \point at (0,0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}

          The set \cB is not orthonormal because, for instance,

            \vec{1 1 1} \cdot \vec{1 1 1} = 3 \neq 1.

          However, we can make it orthonormal by replacing each vector by the unit vector in the direction of each vector:

            \left\{\frac 1{\sqrt3}\vec{1 1 1},\;\frac 1{\sqrt6}\vec{1 -2 1},\;
            \frac 1{\sqrt2}\vec{1 0 -1}\right\}

          is orthonormal.

bluebox.p:
If \{v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m\} is an orthogonal set of vectors, then

  \left\{\frac{v_1}{\|v_1\|},\;\frac{v_2}{\|v_2\|},\ldots,\;\frac{v_m}{\|v_m\|}\right\}

is an orthonormal set.

subsection.p:
Suppose that \{u_1,u_2,\ldots,u_m\} is an orthogonal basis for a subspace W, and let L_i = \Span\{u_i\} for each i=1,2,\ldots,m. Then we see that for any vector x, we have
\spalignsysdelims.. \syseq{x_W = \dfrac{x\cdot u_1}{u_1\cdot u_1}\,u_1 + \dfrac{x\cdot u_2}{u_2\cdot u_2}\,u_2 + \cdots, + \dfrac{x\cdot u_m}{u_m\cdot u_m}\,u_m ; \. = \vphantom{\frac{u_1}{u_1}}x_{L_1}\hfil, + x_{L_2}\hfil, + \cdots, + x_{L_m}\hfil\rlap.}
In other words, for an orthogonal basis, the projection of x onto W is the sum of the projections onto the lines spanned by the basis vectors. In this sense, projection onto a line is the most important example of an orthogonal projection.

solution.p:
The vectors
u_1 = \vec{1 0 -1 0} \qquad u_2 = \vec{0 1 0 -1} \qquad u_3 = \vec{1 1 1 1}
are orthogonal, so we can use the Projection Formula:
\begin{split} x_W \amp= \frac{x\cdot u_1}{u_1\cdot u_1}\,u_1 + \frac{x\cdot u_2}{u_2\cdot u_2}\,u_2 + \frac{x\cdot u_3}{u_3\cdot u_3}\,u_3 \\ \amp= \frac{-3}{2}\vec{1 0 -1 0} + \frac{-3}{2}\vec{0 1 0 -1} + \frac{8}{4}\vec{1 1 1 1} = \frac 12\vec{1 1 7 7} \\ x_{W^\perp} \amp= x - x_W = \frac 12\vec{-1 1 -1 1}. \end{split}
The distance from x to W is
\|x_{W^\perp}\| = \frac 12\sqrt{1+1+1+1} = 1.

bluebox.p:
Let W be a subspace of \R^n with orthogonal basis \cB=\{v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m\} and let x be a vector in W.  Then

  [x]_\cB = \left( \frac{x\cdot u_1}{u_1\cdot u_1},\;
  \frac{x\cdot u_2}{u_2\cdot u_2},\;
  \ldots,\;
  \frac{x\cdot u_m}{u_m\cdot u_m}
  \right).

solution.p:
          Since

            u_1 = \vec{1 2} \qquad u_2 = \vec{-4 2}

          form an orthogonal basis of \R^2, we have

            [x]_\cB = \left(\frac{x\cdot u_1}{u_1\cdot u_1},\;
              \frac{x\cdot u_2}{u_2\cdot u_2} \right)
            = \left(\frac{3\cdot 2}{1^2+2^2},\;
              \frac{3\cdot 2}{(-4)^2+2^2} \right)
            = \left(\frac 65,\;\frac 3{10} \right).


\begin{tikzpicture}[thin border nodes]
  \draw[grid lines] (-5,-1) grid (2,4);
  \draw[->] (-5,0) -- (2,0);
  \draw[->] (0,-1) -- (0,4);
